<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Jerry Hick; Kevin Johnson, N, ; Martin Henderson 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 O.J.'S FINER MOMENT: The last time O.J. Simpson made a public appearance in 
Orange County, he made a lot of friends and did a lot of good for his alma 
mater, USC. . . . La Galleria D'Arte in Newport Beach had asked Simpson to 
autograph copies of a LeRoy Neiman serigraph of his famous run against UCLA 
that sent the Trojans to the 1968 Rose Bowl. Simpson appeared gratis at the art 
gallery on March 20, on condition that it donate $100,000 to USC. . . . "It was 
a long evening and he was just charming," says co-owner Eileen Inderbieten. 
"Our customers have been calling us all week; we're all in shock about what has 
happened." The autographed serigraphs were $3,500 then; $5,000 now, with only a 
few left. 
</P>
<P>
 NO FAINT PRAISE: Sheriff Brad Gates on more than one occasion has found 
himself at odds with members of the Board of Supervisors. But Tuesday, the 
board was all praise for the job his deputies did in the dramatic pursuit of 
O.J. Simpson (B4). . . . "Clearly, this was an extremely delicate and 
potentially dangerous situation that required effective communication and 
coordination," said Supervisor Gaddi H. Vasquez. "And they did it with the 
whole nation watching." 
</P>
<P>
 LITTLE RIPPLES: The Splash is unbeaten in Continental Indoor Soccer League 
play. But the downside: They trail 10 teams in home attendance. The Splash 
averaged just 3,816 fans in their first three home games at the Pond of 
Anaheim. . . . Tonight may be different: Fans will get a poster of the 
Mermaids, the team dancers, as the Splash face Detroit at 7:35. Says dancer 
Jeni Waters: "We've all been Rams or Clippers cheerleaders; we're more 
accessible to the Splash crowd and that makes it more satisfying." 
</P>
<P>
 SIDELINE CREW: Being a team cheerleader may not fit some women's lifestyle, 
but such positions are in great demand. The Los Angeles Rams just completed 
tryouts for their 42-member team, with 250 hopefuls. . . . Alisa Denmon, 28, of 
Hollywood made the team for the seventh year, making her the runaway veteran. 
The cheerleading squad is women only, with 25 from Orange County. Average age: 
22. 
</P>
</TEXT>
