<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMON USES OF CATHETERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A catheter is a slender tube, usually plastic, slid into a body cavity or a 
vein for delivering medications or draining fluid. 
</P>
<P>
 Common uses: Some drain the kidney or the bladder. Others are threaded through 
arteries to clear blockages. Smilarly, catheters can be snaked into the heart 
so that X-ray dyes can be infused, helping to show how valves are functioning. 
Specialized catheters called tracheal tubes pass fluid and gas out of the 
lungs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Sidebar; Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA062294-0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 053681 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
